{"title_page": "Love and Other Disasters", "text_new": "{{About||The Sonic Syndicate Album|Love and Other Disasters (album)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n\n{{refimprove|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Love and Other Disasters\n| image          = Love and Other Disasters.jpg\n| caption        = Promotional poster\n| director       = [[Alek Keshishian]]\n| producer       = Alek Keshishian <br> [[Virginie Silla]] <br> [[Luc Besson]] <br> [[David Fincher]]\n| writer         = Alek Keshishian\n| starring       = [[Brittany Murphy]] <br> [[Santiago Cabrera]] <br> [[Matthew Rhys]] <br> [[Catherine Tate]] <br> [[Stephanie Beacham]]\n| music          = [[Alexandre Azaria|Replicant (as Alexandre Azaria)]]\n| cinematography = [[Pierre Morel]]\n| editing        = Nick Arthurs\n| distributor    = [[Europa Corp.]]\n| released       = {{film date|2006}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes\n| country        = France<br>United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $9 million<ref name=\"Hernandez\">{{cite web |last1=Hernandez |first1=Greg |title=My review of \u201cLove and Other Disasters\u201d |url=http://blogs.dailynews.com/outinhollywood/2007/07/20/my-review-of-love-and-other-di/ |accessdate=20 March 2019 |date=20 July 2007}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Love and Other Disasters''''' is a 2006 French-British [[romantic comedy|romantic comedy film]] produced by Ruby Film, [[Europa Corp.]] and Skyline Films presented at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]]. In 2008, it had its UK premiere in London as the gala screening for the [[British Film Institute|BFI]] 22nd London Gay and Lesbian Film Festival. The director and producer were in attendance. [[Brittany Murphy]] portrays an assistant at British ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' who is the catalyst for a group of young friends as they try to find love. OutFest 2007 presented the film as one of their features.<ref name=\"Rooney\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=A Night With Kook & Crook |url=https://perezhilton.com/a-night-with-kook-crook/ |website=perezhilton.com |accessdate=20 March 2019 |date=20 July 2007}}</ref> Originally director Alek Keshishian had wanted [[Gwyneth Paltrow]] to play 'Jacks' but she was at the time pregnant, later Paltrow got a [[Cameo appearance|cameo role]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Premiere Scoop: Brittany Murphy Grabs Paltrow Role |url=https://www.femalefirst.co.uk/movies/movie-news/Brittany+Murphy-37794.html |website=femalefirst.co.uk |accessdate=20 March 2019 |date=21 July 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nEmily \"Jacks\" Jackson, who spent her childhood in America, now lives and works in London, at British [[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]], and shares an apartment with her gay friend Peter Simon, a screenwriter. Afraid to be disappointed by a serious relationship, Jacks prefers to spend her free time with her friends and sleep with her ex-boyfriend, James, whom she doesn't love. Peter, who has never been in a relationship, spends too much time in his dreams and as a result cannot fall in love with a real person. It gets more complicated with the entrance of Paolo, a photography assistant for one of the photographers at Vogue.  As the film develops, they come to realize their mistakes and eventually reach their happy endings.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Brittany Murphy]] as Emily 'Jacks' Jackson\n* [[Matthew Rhys]] as Peter Simon\n* [[Santiago Cabrera]] as Paolo Sarmiento\n* [[Catherine Tate]] as Tallulah Riggs-Wentworth \n* [[Elliot Cowan]] as James Wildstone\n* [[Adam Rayner]] as Tom / Fantasy David\n* [[Jamie Sives]] as Finlay McMillian\n* [[Will Keen]] as David Williams\n* Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Anscombre as Sascha Santori\n* [[Stephanie Beacham]] as Felicity Riggs-Wentworth\n* Daniel Lob\u00e9 as Freedom\n* Samantha Bloom as Pandora (as Sam Bloom)\n* Jamie Honeybourne as Unicorn Gallagher\n* Robert Chilcott as Art Patron\n* [[Dawn French]] as Therapist\n* [[Michael Lerner (actor)|Michael Lerner]] as Marvin Bernstein\n* [[Gwyneth Paltrow]] as herself playing Jacks (Cameo)\n* [[Orlando Bloom]] as himself playing Paolo (Cameo)\n\n==Reception==\nDavid Rooney of [[ Variety (magazine)|Variety]] noted on 10 September 2006, \"wanly conceived effort looks an unlikely bet for significant bigscreen dates\" and \"Keshishian\u2019s script is sloppy in both setting up and sustaining the sexual identity confusion that fuels the comic engine\".<ref name=\"Rooney\">{{cite news |last1=Rooney |first1=David |title=Love and Other Disasters |url=https://variety.com/2006/film/markets-festivals/love-and-other-disasters-1200513568/ |accessdate=20 March 2019 |date=10 September 2006}}</ref>\n\nGreg Hernandez of 'Out in Hollywood' on 20 July 2007 stated \"a damned entertaining film\", \"well-written and well-directed by Alek Keshishian and wonderfully acted\" and \"includes a hilarious scene featuring cameos by Gwyneth Paltrow and Orlando Bloom\"<ref name=\"Hernandez\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0452643}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|1194842_love_and_other_disasters}}\n* {{Amg movie|326488}}\n\n{{Luc Besson}}\n\n[[Category:2006 films]]\n[[Category:2000s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French comedy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:British LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:French LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Alek Keshishian]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Luc Besson]]\n\n\n{{2000s-romantic-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About||The Sonic Syndicate Album|Love and Other Disasters (album)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n\n{{refimprove|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Love and Other Disasters\n| image          = Love and Other Disasters.jpg\n| caption        = Promotional poster\n| director       = [[Alek Keshishian]]\n| producer       = Alek Keshishian <br> [[Virginie Silla]] <br> [[Luc Besson]] <br> [[David Fincher]]\n| writer         = Alek Keshishian\n| starring       = [[Brittany Murphy]] <br> [[Santiago Cabrera]] <br> [[Matthew Rhys]] <br> [[Catherine Tate]] <br> [[Stephanie Beacham]]\n| music          = [[Alexandre Azaria|Replicant (as Alexandre Azaria)]]\n| cinematography = [[Pierre Morel]]\n| editing        = Nick Arthurs\n| distributor    = [[Europa Corp.]]\n| released       = {{film date|2006}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes\n| country        = France<br>United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $9 million<ref name=\"Hernandez\">{{cite web |last1=Hernandez |first1=Greg |title=My review of \u201cLove and Other Disasters\u201d |url=http://blogs.dailynews.com/outinhollywood/2007/07/20/my-review-of-love-and-other-di/ |accessdate=20 March 2019 |date=20 July 2007}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Love and Other Disasters''''' is a 2006 [[romantic comedy|romantic comedy film]] produced by Ruby Film, [[Europa Corp.]] and Skyline Films presented at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]]. In 2008, it had its UK premiere in London as the gala screening for the [[British Film Institute|BFI]] 22nd London Gay and Lesbian Film Festival. The director and producer were in attendance. [[Brittany Murphy]] portrays an assistant at British ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' who is the catalyst for a group of young friends as they try to find love. OutFest 2007 presented the film as one of their features.<ref name=\"Rooney\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=A Night With Kook & Crook |url=https://perezhilton.com/a-night-with-kook-crook/ |website=perezhilton.com |accessdate=20 March 2019 |date=20 July 2007}}</ref> Originally director Alek Keshishian had wanted [[Gwyneth Paltrow]] to play 'Jacks' but she was at the time pregnant, later Paltrow got a [[Cameo appearance|cameo role]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Premiere Scoop: Brittany Murphy Grabs Paltrow Role |url=https://www.femalefirst.co.uk/movies/movie-news/Brittany+Murphy-37794.html |website=femalefirst.co.uk |accessdate=20 March 2019 |date=21 July 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nEmily \"Jacks\" Jackson, who spent her childhood in America, now lives and works in London, at British [[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]], and shares an apartment with her gay friend Peter Simon, a screenwriter. Afraid to be disappointed by a serious relationship, Jacks prefers to spend her free time with her friends and sleep with her ex-boyfriend, James, whom she doesn't love. Peter, who has never been in a relationship, spends too much time in his dreams and as a result cannot fall in love with a real person. It gets more complicated with the entrance of Paolo, a photography assistant for one of the photographers at Vogue.  As the film develops, they come to realize their mistakes and eventually reach their happy endings.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Brittany Murphy]] as Emily 'Jacks' Jackson\n* [[Matthew Rhys]] as Peter Simon\n* [[Santiago Cabrera]] as Paolo Sarmiento\n* [[Catherine Tate]] as Tallulah Riggs-Wentworth \n* [[Elliot Cowan]] as James Wildstone\n* [[Adam Rayner]] as Tom / Fantasy David\n* [[Jamie Sives]] as Finlay McMillian\n* [[Will Keen]] as David Williams\n* Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Anscombre as Sascha Santori\n* [[Stephanie Beacham]] as Felicity Riggs-Wentworth\n* Daniel Lob\u00e9 as Freedom\n* Samantha Bloom as Pandora (as Sam Bloom)\n* Jamie Honeybourne as Unicorn Gallagher\n* Robert Chilcott as Art Patron\n* [[Dawn French]] as Therapist\n* [[Michael Lerner (actor)|Michael Lerner]] as Marvin Bernstein\n* [[Gwyneth Paltrow]] as herself playing Jacks (Cameo)\n* [[Orlando Bloom]] as himself playing Paolo (Cameo)\n\n==Reception==\nDavid Rooney of [[ Variety (magazine)|Variety]] noted on 10 September 2006, \"wanly conceived effort looks an unlikely bet for significant bigscreen dates\" and \"Keshishian\u2019s script is sloppy in both setting up and sustaining the sexual identity confusion that fuels the comic engine\".<ref name=\"Rooney\">{{cite news |last1=Rooney |first1=David |title=Love and Other Disasters |url=https://variety.com/2006/film/markets-festivals/love-and-other-disasters-1200513568/ |accessdate=20 March 2019 |date=10 September 2006}}</ref>\n\nGreg Hernandez of 'Out in Hollywood' on 20 July 2007 stated \"a damned entertaining film\", \"well-written and well-directed by Alek Keshishian and wonderfully acted\" and \"includes a hilarious scene featuring cameos by Gwyneth Paltrow and Orlando Bloom\"<ref name=\"Hernandez\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0452643}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|1194842_love_and_other_disasters}}\n* {{Amg movie|326488}}\n\n{{Luc Besson}}\n\n[[Category:2006 films]]\n[[Category:2000s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French comedy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:British LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:French LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Alek Keshishian]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Luc Besson]]\n\n\n{{2000s-romantic-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Love_and_Other_Disasters"}
{"title_page": "1998 OFC Nations Cup squads", "text_new": "{{under construction}}\n{{Main article|1998 OFC Nations Cup}}\n\nThe '''1998 OFC Nations Cup''' was an international football tournament that was held in [[Brisbane]], [[Australia]] from 25 September to 4 October 1998. The 6 national teams involved in the tournament were required to register a squad of players; only players in these squads were eligible to take part in the tournament.  The [[1998 Melanesia Cup]] and the [[1998 Polynesia Cup]] were used to find the four qualifiers for the finals tournament ([[Fiji national football team|Fiji]] and [[Vanuatu national football team|Vanuatu]] from Melanesia and [[Tahiti national football team|Tahiti]] and [[Cook Islands national football team|Cook Islands]] from Polynesia respectively), to move on and join [[Australia national football team|Australia]] and [[New Zealand national football team|New Zealand]] at the main tournament.\n\nPlayers marked ([[Captain (association football)|c]]) were named as captain for their national squad. Players' club teams and players' age are as of 25 September 1998 \u2013 the tournament's opening day.\n\n==Squad lists==\n===Australia===\nCoach: {{flagicon|ARG}} [[Raul Blanco]]\n{{nat fs start}}\n{{nat fs player|no=1|pos=GK|name=[[Jason Petkovic]]|age={{Birth date and age2|1998|9|25|1972|12|7|df=y}}|caps=|club=[[Adelaide City FC|Adelaide City]]|clubnat=AUS}}\n{{nat fs player|no=2|pos=DF|name=[[Robert Trajkovski]]|age={{Birth date and age2|1998|9|25|1972|7|24|df=y}}|caps=|club=[[Perth Glory FC|Perth Glory]]|clubnat=AUS}}\n{{nat fs player|no=3|pos=DF|name=[[Fausto De Amicis]]|age={{Birth date and age2|1998|9|25|1968|6|26|df=y}}|caps=|club=[[South Melbourne FC|South Melbourne]]|clubnat=AUS}}\n{{nat fs player|no=4|pos=DF|name=[[Glenn Gwynne]]|age={{Birth date and age2|1998|9|25|1972|2|22|df=y}}|caps=|club=[[Brisbane Strikers FC|Brisbane Strikers]]|clubnat=AUS}}\n{{nat fs player|no=5|pos=DF|name=[[Alex Tobin]] ([[Captain (association fo