\n| homepage         = [http://www.powells.com/ www.powells.com]\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n\n'''Powell's Books''' is a chain of [[bookstore]]s in [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]], and its surrounding [[Portland metropolitan area|metropolitan area]]. Powell's headquarters, dubbed '''Powell's City of Books''', claims to be the largest [[independent bookstore|independent new and used bookstore]] in the world.<ref name=\"burnside\">{{cite web | title = Powell's Books on Burnside | publisher = Powell's City of Books | url = http://www.powells.com/info/places/burnsideinfo.html | accessdate = 2009-03-12}}</ref> Powell's City of Books is located in the [[Pearl District]] on the edge of [[Downtown Portland|downtown]] and occupies a full [[city block]] between NW 10th and 11th Avenues and between W. Burnside and NW Couch Streets. It contains over {{convert|68,000|ft2}}, about 1.6 acres of retail floor space. CNN rates it one of the \"coolest\" bookstores in the world.<ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://edition.cnn.com/2014/07/23/travel/worlds-coolest-bookstores/index.html \n | title = World's coolest bookstores\n | author = Frances Cha\n | publisher = CNN\n | date = July 30, 2014\n | accessdate = 2016-06-18\n}}</ref>\n\nThe City of Books has nine color-coded rooms and over 3,500 different sections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.powells.com/locations/powells-city-of-books|title=Powell's City of Books at Burnside - Powell's Books|website=www.powells.com}}</ref>\nThe inventory for its retail and online sales is over four million new, used, [[Book collecting|rare]], and out-of-print books.<ref>{{cite web | title = Internet Retailer Best of the Web 2006 | publisher = [[Internet Retailer]] | url = http://www.internetretailer.com/article.asp?id=16892#powells | accessdate = 2007-08-28 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090214233922/http://www.internetretailer.com/article.asp?id=16892#powells | archivedate = February 14, 2009 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>  Powell's buys around 3,000 used books a day.<ref name=\"burnside\" />\n\n==History==\n===20th century===\nPowell's was founded by Walter Powell in 1971. His son, Michael Powell, had started a bookstore in [[Chicago, Illinois]], in 1970 which specialized in used, rare, and discounted books, primarily of an academic and scholarly nature. In 1979, Michael Powell joined his father in Portland, right after his father's store was not offered a lease renewal; within a year, they found the location that became its current headquarters.<ref name=\"pandw2010\"/>  Michael bought the bookstore from his father in 1982.<ref name=\"funduni\"/>\n\nIn 1984,<ref name=\"suburb\"/><ref name=oreg-25nov84>\"Loehmann's Plaza gains 85 percent occupancy\". (November 25, 1984). ''The Sunday Oregonian'', p. D11.</ref> Powell's opened its first branch store, in a suburban shopping center named Loehmann's Plaza<ref name=oreg-25nov84/> (later renamed Cascade Plaza),<ref name=oreg-2june87>\"Beaverton retail mall rechristened\". (June 2, 1987). ''The Oregonian'', p. D8.</ref> near [[Washington Square (Oregon)|Washington Square]]. The new branch was not a replica of its City of Books location; Powell was concerned that the \"edgy\" neighborhood of its headquarters location was limiting its customer base, so the new store was \"fairly fancy\" with white shelving, a tile floor, and banners over the aisles.<ref name=\"pandw2010\"/>  It was also four times the size of the typical chain bookstore.<ref name=\"funduni\"/>\n\nA travel bookstore was established in 1985 on [[Pioneer Courthouse Square]], and other stores followed, one a year for the next few years.<ref name=\"pandw2010\"/> By the early 1990s, Powell's bookstores were part of the resurgence of the [[independent bookstore]], which collectively made 32 percent of book sales in the U.S.<ref name=\"funduni\"/>  The travel store closed in 2005.<ref name=\"oreg-2005feb7\">Nkrumah, Wade (February 7, 2005). \"Food carts at Pioneer Square may be ousted\". ''The Oregonian'', p. C1.</ref>\n\n[[File:Powells-City-of-Books-NW-Entrance Portland-OR 2008-May.jpg|thumb|Powell's NW 11th & Couch entrance, featuring the \"Pillar of Books\".]]\nPowell's established its Internet presence in 1993, beginning with email and [[File transfer protocol|FTP]]-based access to its technical bookstore; it has since expanded to incorporate fiction and other genres as a traditional [[ecommerce]] site.<ref>[http://www.powells.com/info/details.html History of Powells.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120716182907/http://www.powells.com/info/details.html |date=July 16, 2012 }} from its website</ref>  Their website was established in 1994, before [[Amazon.com]], and has contributed substantially to the chain's recent growth.<ref>{{cite news | first = Lisa | last = Baker | title = Powell\u2019s success story adds a chapter | newspaper = [[Portland Tribune]] | date = March 19, 2004 | url = http://thevig.portlandtribune.com/news/print_story.php?story_id=23515 | accessdate = 2012-08-27 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe City of Books location grew to its current size after an expansion that opened in 1999; it included a new entrance facing the [[Pearl District]] which featured the \"Pillar of Books\", a [[Tenino, Washington|Tenino]] sandstone carving depicting a stack of eight of the world's great books, on a base with the inscription  \"Buy the book, read the book, enjoy the book, sell the book\" in Latin.<ref name=\"funduni\"/>  For the year ending June 2000, Powell's revenue was $41.8 million.<ref name=\"funduni\">[http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/Powells-Books-Inc-Company-History.html Powell's Books, Inc.] from fundinguniverse.com</ref>\n\n===21st century===\nIn 2002, Powell's was cited by ''[[USA Today]]'' as one of America's 10 best bookstores.<ref name=\"10 Great Places\">''USA Today'', January 21, 2002. [https://www.usatoday.com/travel/destinations/10great/2003-09-29-books_x.htm?loc=interstitialskip \"10 Great Places to Crawl Between the Covers\"]. Retrieved 2016-06-18.</ref>\n\nIn January 2008, Powell's announced plans to expand the downtown City of Books by adding as many as two floors to the store's southeast corner.  The expansion was due to add at least {{convert|10000|sqft|m2}} of new retail space.<ref>{{cite web| last=Bennett| first=Sam| title= New design for Powell's Books features an art cube | url= http://djcoregon.com/news/2008/11/13/new-design-for-powells-books-features-an-art-cube/ | newspaper= [[Daily Journal of Commerce]] |date= November 13, 2008 | accessdate=2016-06-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first = Laura | last = Gunderson | title = Powell's plans expansion in two years | newspaper = The Oregonian | date = January 22, 2008 | url = http://blog.oregonlive.com/breakingnews/2008/01/powells_plans_expansion_in_two.html | accessdate = 2007-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Edward |last=Nawotka |title=Powell\u2019s to Expand Flagship in 2010, Absorb Technical Store |work=Publishers Weekly |date=January 23, 2008 |url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/article/CA6524823.html |accessdate=2007-01-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080209233242/http://www.publishersweekly.com/article/CA6524823.html |archivedate=February 9, 2008 }}</ref>  Plans submitted to the Portland Design Commission in November 2008 called for a rooftop garden atop the new addition and an \"art cube\" over a redesigned main entrance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chatterbox.typepad.com/portlandarchitecture/2008/11/powells-unveils-design-for-new-entrance-to-flagship-store.html|title=Bestseller or return for refund? Powell's unveils design for new entrance to flagship store|website=Portland Architecture}}</ref>\n[[File:PowellsTechnicalBooks.jpg|thumb|Powell's Technical Books at its original [[North Park Blocks]] location (closed in 2010).]]\nIn March 2010, Michael Powell confirmed plans to hand over management of the business to his daughter Emily as of July.<ref name=\"pandw2010\"/>  That same month, Powell's announced it would close its technical bookstore on the [[North Park Blocks]], moving its sections on math, science, computing, engineering, construction and transportation into \"Powell\u2019s Books Building 2\" at the corner of 10th and Couch Street, near the main City of Books location; the consolidation was in response to a five-year decline in [[brick-and-mortar]] sales of technical books in favor of online sales.<ref name=\"pbj201003\">{{cite news| title= Powell's to move Tech Store| date= March 4, 2010 | url= http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2010/03/01/daily57.html | newspaper= [[Portland Business Journal]] | accessdate=2010-12-07}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, Powell's announced it had bought 7,000 books from the library of author [[Anne Rice]]; Powell's offers these [[association copy|association copies]] on their website.<ref>{{cite news| title= Powell's Books buys Anne Rice collection | date= October 26, 2010 | url= http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2010/10/26/powells-books-buys-anne-rice-collection.html | first= Andy |last= Giegerich | newspaper= [[Portland Business Journal]] | accessdate=2010-12-07}}</ref>   The bookstore was revealed as a charter member of the [[Google eBooks]] service when the news was announced by Google on December 6, 2010.<ref name=\"googebook2010\">{{cite web| url= http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2010/12/discover-more-than-3-million-google.html | title= Discover more than 3 million Google eBooks from your choice of booksellers and devices | work= Official blog | publisher=[[Google]] | date= December 6, 2010| accessdate=2010-12-06}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2011, Powell's participated in [[Google Offers]] during that service's first month of operation; according to [[TechCrunch]]&mdash;which characterized Powell's as a \"Portland institution\"&mdash;\"5,000 Powell\u2019s vouchers sold out in a matter of hours\", making it \"most popular deal in the month.\"<ref>{{cite news| first= Rocky |last= Agrawal| url= https://techcrunch.com/2011/07/04/google-offers-versus-groupon-portland/| title= Google Offers Versus Groupon: The Portland Throwdown | work=[[TechCrunch]] | date= July 4, 2011| accessdate=2011-07-11}}</ref>\n\nStarting in May 2012,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ondemandbooks.com/docs/powells-the-EBM-arrives.pdf| format= PDF| title= The Espresso Book Machine Arrives at Powell's Books | work= Press release| date= May 4, 2012 |publisher=OnDemandBooks.com| accessdate=2012-05-14}}</ref>  Powell's began offering access to [[print on demand]] books via the [[Espresso Book Machine]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://ondemandbooks.com/ebm_locations_list.php | title= EBM Locations: List View | publisher= OnDemandBooks.com| accessdate= 2012-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first = Alison | last = Hallett | title = More on Powells' New Espresso Book Machine  | newspaper = [[The Portland Mercury]] | date = May 4, 2012 | url = http://www.portlandmercury.com/BlogtownPDX/archives/2012/05/04/more-on-powells-new-espresso-book-machine | accessdate = 2014-06-06}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2013, Emily Powell announced that Miriam Sontz, the company's chief operating officer, would take over as chief executive officer.<ref>{{cite news |title=Owner, new CEO of Powell's Books see strength in brick and mortar |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2013/04/owner_new_ceo_of_powells_books.html |publisher=The Oregonian/OregonLive |date=25 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2014 \"Powell\u2019s Books Building 2\" was closed and the technical books at that location were moved into the main City of Books location.\n\nCEO Miriam Sontz retired in January 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=New Laws, Northwest Fires, Changes In The Book Biz |url=https://www.opb.org/radio/programs/thinkoutloud/segment/daylight-saving-time-changes-in-the-book-biz-new-laws/ |publisher=OPB |date=January 3, 2019}}</ref> Emily Powell remains president and owner.<ref>{{cite news |title=CEO of Powell's Books will retire in January 2019 |url=https://katu.com/news/local/ceo-of-powells-books-miriam-sontz-will-retire-in-january-2019 |publisher=KATU News}}</ref>\n\nPowell's temporarily closed all of its physical locations and laid off the vast majority of its staff in March 2020 as a result of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]. After a large surge in online orders from customers, the store was able to rehire about 100 former employees to fulfill them while maintaining [[social distancing]] guidelines.<ref>http://web.archive.org/web/20200329201856/http://www.powells.com/featured/communitymessage</ref>\n\n===Labor relations===\nIn 1991, following some post-holiday lay-offs, some of Powell's employees formed an organizing committee, seeking to become part of the Oregon Public Employees Union (OPEU).  They got more than 35% of the employees to sign union cards but chose not to file for a union certification election because less than 65% had signed, a threshold suggested by the OPEU.<ref name=\"ilwu\">[http://www.ilwulocal5.com/about/we-are-the-ilwu/we-are-ilwu-local-5/ilwu-local-5-powells-books/history ILWU Local 5: A Brief History of Local 5: Powell\u2019s Books, Inc.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110116051423/http://www.ilwulocal5.com/about/we-are-the-ilwu/we-are-ilwu-local-5/ilwu-local-5-powells-books/history |date=January 16, 2011 }} from the [[International Longshore and Warehouse Union|ILWU]] Local 5 website</ref>  In response to issues identified by the organizing employees, Powell's updated and expanded its employee handbook in April 1992 with changes that addressed processes for problem solving and grievances, the probation and termination procedure, and other employee assistance, among other changes.\n\nIn September 1998, email from Powell's managers announcing reductions in employee\u2019s wage increases prompted the creation of a new organizing committee of 26 employees.  They chose the [[International Longshore and Warehouse Union]] (ILWU) because they could charter their own self-governing [[local union]] which would include about 350 employees serving in a variety of jobs in all stores and in the Internet, corporate, and shipping departments. By March 1999, they filed for a union certification election with the [[National Labor Relations Board]]. A month later, by a vote of 161\u2013155, ILWU Local 5 became official.<ref name=\"ilwu\"/>\n\nIn September 1999, ILWU Local 5 met for the first time with Powell's management, to begin the contract bargaining process.  After some early successes, 2000 saw a slowdown in the discussions, followed by rallies, filings of [[unfair labor practice]]s, an unsuccessful decertification campaign, a one-day shutdown of the shipping department (accompanied by the slashing of a van's tire), and [[Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service (United States)|federal mediation]].  A three-year contract was finally announced in August 2000.<ref name=\"ilwu\"/>\n\nIn February 2011 Powell's announced the layoffs of 31 employees, over 7% of its unionized workforce, in \u201cresponse to the unprecedented, rapidly changing nature of the book industry\". It was the first round of layoffs since the store\u2019s workers formed a union. A union representative said that Powell's had reduced its workforce by about 40 in the prior year through attrition, but felt that layoffs were still necessary because of a decline in sales of new books and a rise in health care costs.<ref name =\"NY Times Arts Beat\">{{cite news| title= Powell\u2019s Books Announces Layoffs | date= February 9, 2011 | url= http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/02/09/powells-books-announces-layoffs/ | first= Julie |last= Bosman | newspaper= [[The New York Times]] Arts Beat blog | accessdate=2011-02-09}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Powell's announced the closing of its five locations and the termination of nearly all employees in mid-March 2020.<ref name=\"latimes2020\">{{cite news |title=Powell\u2019s, Portland\u2019s beloved indie bookstore, will lay off most workers |last1=Pineda |first1=Dorany |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/books/story/2020-03-18/powells-portlands-beloved-indie-bookstore-lays-off-most-workers |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=March 18, 2020 |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The letter released by CEO Emily Powell on March 17, 2020, did not disclose the exact number of employees that were laid off. However, roughly 85% of the 400 members of the company's unionized workforce were terminated.<ref name=\"oregonlive2020\">{{cite news |title=Powell's expands coronavirus layoff, warns it will be 'several months' before normal operations |last1=Rogoway |first1=Mike |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/powells-expands-coronavirus-layoff-warns-it-will-be-several-months-before-normal-operations.html |work=The Oregonian |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> More than 100 former staffers were then rehired to fulfill a large surge of online orders.<ref>http://web.archive.org/web/20200329201856/http://www.powells.com/featured/communitymessage</ref>\n\n=== Politics ===\nPowell's Books was a key opponent of Oregon's [[Oregon Ballot Measure 97 (2016)|Measure 97]], which would have raised corporate taxes to fund schools, healthcare and senior services. Michael Powell contributed $25,000 to the opposition campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://secure.sos.state.or.us/orestar/gotoPublicTransactionDetail.do?tranRsn=2313889|title=Oregon Secretary Of State|website=secure.sos.state.or.us|access-date=2017-01-19}}</ref> Powell's Books was featured in television ads for the No campaign,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Oregon_Business_Tax_Increase,_Measure_97_(2016)|title=Oregon Business Tax Increase, Measure 97 (2016) - Ballotpedia|language=en|access-date=2017-01-19}}</ref> and Emily Powell signed a statement opposing the measure in the voter's pamphlet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sos.oregon.gov/elections/Documents/pamphlet/november-general-2016.aspx|title=Online Voters' Pamphlet {{!}} Oregon Secretary of State|website=sos.oregon.gov|access-date=2017-01-19}}</ref>\n\n== List of locations ==\n[[File:Powell's Books at Cedar Hills Crossing, mall-interior entrance.jpg|thumb|right|Powell's Books at Cedar Hills Crossing]]\nIn addition to its \"City of Books\" location, Powell's Books also has several smaller stores: \n*a {{convert|32500|sqft|adj=on}} general bookstore with the \"largest children's book section of any book store on the West Coast\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.powells.com/locations/powells-books-at-cedar-hills-crossing|title=Powells Books At Cedar Hills Crossing|website=www.powells.com}}</ref> located at [[Cedar Hills Crossing]] in [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]] and opened in November 2006, replacing a 22-year-old location near [[Washington Square (Oregon)|Washington Square]] that was less than half the size;<ref name=\"suburb\">[http://www.powells.com/info/places/beavertoninfo.html Powell's Books at Cedar Hills Crossing] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070227132702/http://www.powells.com/info/places/beavertoninfo.html |date=February 27, 2007 }} from the company's website. Retrieved 2012-07-14.</ref>\n*another in Portland's [[Hawthorne, Portland, Oregon|Hawthorne District]];\n*a store with cooking and gardening materials two spaces east of the Hawthorne store (it was announced in January 2016 that Powell's will be taking over the lease of the space between the general interest store and the home and garden store and combine the two stores into one, with larger children's books and authors' event sections).<ref name=\"expand Hawthorne\">{{cite news|last=Marum|first=Anna|title=Powell's Books to expand Hawthorne location|newspaper=The Oregonian|date=January 6, 2016|orig-year=print-edition date January 8, p. C1|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/window-shop/index.ssf/2016/01/powells_hawthorne_expansion.html|accessdate=2016-02-01}}</ref>\n*one store at the [[Portland International Airport]], offering popular fiction and non-fiction, \"choice\" used books, games, toys, and gifts.<ref>[http://www.powells.com/info/places/airportinfo.html Powell's Books at PDX] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060717040156/http://www.powells.com/info/places/airportinfo.html |date=July 17, 2006 }} from the company's website</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Oregon}}\n* [[Cameron's Books and Magazines]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.powells.com/ Powell's website], including a [https://web.archive.org/web/20140613100109/http://www.powells.com/info/citytour.html tour of the City of Books]\n\n{{coord|45|31|24.04|N|122|40|53.71|W|region:US-OR_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{LA Times Innovator's Award}}\n{{Pearl District, Portland, Oregon}}\n\n[[Category:1971 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1971]]\n[[Category:Antiquarian booksellers]]\n[[Category:Book selling websites]]\n[[Category:Bookstores established in the 20th century]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:E-book suppliers]]\n[[Category:Independent bookstores of the United States]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 1993]]\n[[Category:Online retailers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Pearl District, Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1971]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Bookstore chain selling new and used books}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Powell's Books\n| logo             = [[File:PowellsBookstore.jpg|200px|Powell's NW 10th & Burnside entrance.]]\n| type             = \n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = {{Start date|1971}}\n| founder          = Walter Powell\n| owner            = Walter Powell (1971\u20131982), Michael Powell (1982\u20132010), Emily Powell (2010-present)<ref name=\"funduni\"/><ref name=\"pandw2010\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Chamberlin |first1=Jeremiah |title=Inside Indie Bookstores: Powell\u2019s Books in Portland, Oregon |url=https://www.pw.org/print/567509?destination=content/inside_indie_bookstores_powell_s_books_in_portland_oregon |publisher=Poets & Writers}}</ref>\n| key_people       = Emily Powell<ref name=\"pandw2010\"/>\n| defunct          = \n| location_city    = Portland, Oregon\n| location_country = United States\n| location         = \n| locations        = Five (four full-service locations and one specialty bookstore)\n| area_served      = [[Portland metropolitan area]]\n| industry         = [[Retailing|Specialty retail]]\n| products         = New, used and rare books, magazines, cards, and sidelines<ref name=\"pandw2010\">[http://www.pw.org/print/567509?destination=content/inside_indie_bookstores_powell_s_books_in_portland_oregon Inside Indie Bookstores: Powell\u2019s Books in Portland, Oregon] from the March/April 2010 issue of ''[[Poets & Writers|Poets & Writers Magazine]]''. Retrieved 2016-06-18.</ref>\n| production       =\n| services         = \n| revenue          = $45 million (as of 2009)<ref name=\"pbj201003\"/>\n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| aum              = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| num_employees    = about 500<ref name=\"pandw2010\"/>\n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = [http://www.powells.com/ www.powells.com]\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n\n'''Powell's Books''' is a chain of [[bookstore]]s in [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]], and its surrounding [[Portland metropolitan area|metropolitan area]]. Powell's headquarters, dubbed '''Powell's City of Books''', claims to be the largest [[independent bookstore|independent new and used bookstore]] in the world.<ref name=\"burnside\">{{cite web | title = Powell's Books on Burnside | publisher = Powell's City of Books | url = http://www.powells.com/info/places/burnsideinfo.html | accessdate = 2009-03-12}}</ref> Powell's City of Books is located in the [[Pearl District]] on the edge of [[Downtown Portland|downtown]] and occupies a full [[city block]] between NW 10th and 11th Avenues and between W. Burnside and NW Couch Streets. It contains over {{convert|68,000|ft2}}, about 1.6 acres of retail floor space. CNN rates it one of the \"coolest\" bookstores in the world.<ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://edition.cnn.com/2014/07/23/travel/worlds-coolest-bookstores/index.html \n | title = World's coolest bookstores\n | author = Frances Cha\n | publisher = CNN\n | date = July 30, 2014\n | accessdate = 2016-06-18\n}}</ref>\n\nThe City of Books has nine color-coded rooms and over 3,500 different sections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.powells.com/locations/powells-city-of-books|title=Powell's City of Books at Burnside - Powell's Books|website=www.powells.com}}</ref>\n\nThe inventory for its retail and online sales is over four million new, used, [[Book collecting|rare]], and out-of-print books.<ref>{{cite web | title = Internet Retailer Best of the Web 2006 | publisher = [[Internet Retailer]] | url = http://www.internetretailer.com/article.asp?id=16892#powells | accessdate = 2007-08-28 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090214233922/http://www.internetretailer.com/article.asp?id=16892#powells | archivedate = February 14, 2009 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>  Powell's buys around 3,000 used books a day.<ref name=\"burnside\" />\n\n==History==\n===20th century===\nPowell's was founded by Walter Powell in 1971. His son, Michael Powell, had started a bookstore in [[Chicago, Illinois]], in 1970 which specialized in used, rare, and discounted books, primarily of an academic and scholarly nature. In 1979, Michael Powell joined his father in Portland, right after his father's store was not offered a lease renewal; within a year, they found the location that became its current headquarters.<ref name=\"pandw2010\"/>  Michael bought the bookstore from his father in 1982.<ref name=\"funduni\"/>\n\nIn 1984,<ref name=\"suburb\"/><ref name=oreg-25nov84>\"Loehmann's Plaza gains 85 percent occupancy\". (November 25, 1984). ''The Sunday Oregonian'', p. D11.</ref> Powell's opened its first branch store, in a suburban shopping center named Loehmann's Plaza<ref name=oreg-25nov84/> (later renamed Cascade Plaza),<ref name=oreg-2june87>\"Beaverton retail mall rechristened\". (June 2, 1987). ''The Oregonian'', p. D8.</ref> near [[Washington Square (Oregon)|Washington Square]]. The new branch was not a replica of its City of Books location; Powell was concerned that the \"edgy\" neighborhood of its headquarters location was limiting its customer base, so the new store was \"fairly fancy\" with white shelving, a tile floor, and banners over the aisles.<ref name=\"pandw2010\"/>  It was also four times the size of the typical chain bookstore.<ref name=\"funduni\"/>\n\nA travel bookstore was established in 1985 on [[Pioneer Courthouse Square]], and other stores followed, one a year for the next few years.<ref name=\"pandw2010\"/> By the early 1990s, Powell's bookstores were part of the resurgence of the [[independent bookstore]], which collectively made 32 percent of book sales in the U.S.<ref name=\"funduni\"/>  The travel store closed in 2005.<ref name=\"oreg-2005feb7\">Nkrumah, Wade (February 7, 2005). \"Food carts at Pioneer Square may be ousted\". ''The Oregonian'', p. C1.</ref>\n\n[[File:Powells-City-of-Books-NW-Entrance Portland-OR 2008-May.jpg|thumb|Powell's NW 11th & Couch entrance, featuring the \"Pillar of Books\".]]\nPowell's established its Internet presence in 1993, beginning with email and [[File transfer protocol|FTP]]-based access to its technical bookstore; it has since expanded to incorporate fiction and other genres as a traditional [[ecommerce]] site.<ref>[http://www.powells.com/info/details.html History of Powells.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120716182907/http://www.powells.com/info/details.html |date=July 16, 2012 }} from its website</ref>  Their website was established in 1994, before [[Amazon.com]], and has contributed substantially to the chain's recent growth.<ref>{{cite news | first = Lisa | last = Baker | title = Powell\u2019s success story adds a chapter | newspaper = [[Portland Tribune]] | date = March 19, 2004 | url = http://thevig.portlandtribune.com/news/print_story.php?story_id=23515 | accessdate = 2012-08-27 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe City of Books location grew to its current size after an expansion that opened in 1999; it included a new entrance facing the [[Pearl District]] which featured the \"Pillar of Books\", a [[Tenino, Washington|Tenino]] sandstone carving depicting a stack of eight of the world's great books, on a base with the inscription  \"Buy the book, read the book, enjoy the book, sell the book\" in Latin.<ref name=\"funduni\"/>  For the year ending June 2000, Powell's revenue was $41.8 million.<ref name=\"funduni\">[http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/Powells-Books-Inc-Company-History.html Powell's Books, Inc.] from fundinguniverse.com</ref>\n\n===21st century===\nIn 2002, Powell's was cited by ''[[USA Today]]'' as one of America's 10 best bookstores.<ref name=\"10 Great Places\">''USA Today'', January 21, 2002. [https://www.usatoday.com/travel/destinations/10great/2003-09-29-books_x.htm?loc=interstitialskip \"10 Great Places to Crawl Between the Covers\"]. Retrieved 2016-06-18.</ref>\n\nIn January 2008, Powell's announced plans to expand the downtown City of Books by adding as many as two floors to the store's southeast corner.  The expansion was due to add at least {{convert|10000|sqft|m2}} of new retail space.<ref>{{cite web| last=Bennett| first=Sam| title= New design for Powell's Books features an art cube | url= http://djcoregon.com/news/2008/11/13/new-design-for-powells-books-features-an-art-cube/ | newspaper= [[Daily Journal of Commerce]] |date= November 13, 2008 | accessdate=2016-06-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first = Laura | last = Gunderson | title = Powell's plans expansion in two years | newspaper = The Oregonian | date = January 22, 2008 | url = http://blog.oregonlive.com/breakingnews/2008/01/powells_plans_expansion_in_two.html | accessdate = 2007-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Edward |last=Nawotka |title=Powell\u2019s to Expand Flagship in 2010, Absorb Technical Store |work=Publishers Weekly |date=January 23, 2008 |url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/article/CA6524823.html |accessdate=2007-01-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080209233242/http://www.publishersweekly.com/article/CA6524823.html |archivedate=February 9, 2008 }}</ref>  Plans submitted to the Portland Design Commission in November 2008 called for a rooftop garden atop the new addition and an \"art cube\" over a redesigned main entrance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chatterbox.typepad.com/portlandarchitecture/2008/11/powells-unveils-design-for-new-entrance-to-flagship-store.html|title=Bestseller or return for refund? Powell's unveils design for new entrance to flagship store|website=Portland Architecture}}</ref>\n[[File:PowellsTechnicalBooks.jpg|thumb|Powell's Technical Books at its original [[North Park Blocks]] location (closed in 2010).]]\nIn March 2010, Michael Powell confirmed plans to hand over management of the business to his daughter Emily as of July.<ref name=\"pandw2010\"/>  That same month, Powell's announced it would close its technical bookstore on the [[North Park Blocks]], moving its sections on math, science, computing, engineering, construction and transportation into \"Powell\u2019s Books Building 2\" at the corner of 10th and Couch Street, near the main City of Books location; the consolidation was in response to a five-year decline in [[brick-and-mortar]] sales of technical books in favor of online sales.<ref name=\"pbj201003\">{{cite news| title= Powell's to move Tech Store| date= March 4, 2010 | url= http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2010/03/01/daily57.html | newspaper= [[Portland Business Journal]] | accessdate=2010-12-07}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, Powell's announced it had bought 7,000 books from the library of author [[Anne Rice]]; Powell's offers these [[association copy|association copies]] on their website.<ref>{{cite news| title= Powell's Books buys Anne Rice collection | date= October 26, 2010 | url= http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2010/10/26/powells-books-buys-anne-rice-collection.html | first= Andy |last= Giegerich | newspaper= [[Portland Business Journal]] | accessdate=2010-12-07}}</ref>   The bookstore was revealed as a charter member of the [[Google eBooks]] service when the news was announced by Google on December 6, 2010.<ref name=\"googebook2010\">{{cite web| url= http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2010/12/discover-more-than-3-million-google.html | title= Discover more than 3 million Google eBooks from your choice of booksellers and devices | work= Official blog | publisher=[[Google]] | date= December 6, 2010| accessdate=2010-12-06}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2011, Powell's participated in [[Google Offers]] during that service's first month of operation; according to [[TechCrunch]]&mdash;which characterized Powell's as a \"Portland institution\"&mdash;\"5,000 Powell\u2019s vouchers sold out in a matter of hours\", making it \"most popular deal in the month.\"<ref>{{cite news| first= Rocky |last= Agrawal| url= https://techcrunch.com/2011/07/04/google-offers-versus-groupon-portland/| title= Google Offers Versus Groupon: The Portland Throwdown | work=[[TechCrunch]] | date= July 4, 2011| accessdate=2011-07-11}}</ref>\n\nStarting in May 2012,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ondemandbooks.com/docs/powells-the-EBM-arrives.pdf| format= PDF| title= The Espresso Book Machine Arrives at Powell's Books | work= Press release| date= May 4, 2012 |publisher=OnDemandBooks.com| accessdate=2012-05-14}}</ref>  Powell's began offering access to [[print on demand]] books via the [[Espresso Book Machine]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://ondemandbooks.com/ebm_locations_list.php | title= EBM Locations: List View | publisher= OnDemandBooks.com| accessdate= 2012-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first = Alison | last = Hallett | title = More on Powells' New Espresso Book Machine  | newspaper = [[The Portland Mercury]] | date = May 4, 2012 | url = http://www.portlandmercury.com/BlogtownPDX/archives/2012/05/04/more-on-powells-new-espresso-book-machine | accessdate = 2014-06-06}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2013, Emily Powell announced that Miriam Sontz, the company's chief operating officer, would take over as chief executive officer.<ref>{{cite news |title=Owner, new CEO of Powell's Books see strength in brick and mortar |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2013/04/owner_new_ceo_of_powells_books.html |publisher=The Oregonian/OregonLive |date=25 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2014 \"Powell\u2019s Books Building 2\" was closed and the technical books at that location were moved into the main City of Books location.\n\nCEO Miriam Sontz retired in January 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=New Laws, Northwest Fires, Changes In The Book Biz |url=https://www.opb.org/radio/programs/thinkoutloud/segment/daylight-saving-time-changes-in-the-book-biz-new-laws/ |publisher=OPB |date=January 3, 2019}}</ref> Emily Powell remains president and owner.<ref>{{cite news |title=CEO of Powell's Books will retire in January 2019 |url=https://katu.com/news/local/ceo-of-powells-books-miriam-sontz-will-retire-in-january-2019 |publisher=KATU News}}</ref>\n\nPowell's temporarily closed all of its physical locations and laid off the vast majority of its staff in March 2020 as a result of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]. After a large surge in online orders from customers, the store was able to rehire about 100 former employees to fulfill them while maintaining [[social distancing]] guidelines.<ref>http://web.archive.org/web/20200329201856/http://www.powells.com/featured/communitymessage</ref>\n\n===Labor relations===\nIn 1991, following some post-holiday lay-offs, some of Powell's employees formed an organizing committee, seeking to become part of the Oregon Public Employees Union (OPEU).  They got more than 35% of the employees to sign union cards but chose not to file for a union certification election because less than 65% had signed, a threshold suggested by the OPEU.<ref name=\"ilwu\">[http://www.ilwulocal5.com/about/we-are-the-ilwu/we-are-ilwu-local-5/ilwu-local-5-powells-books/history ILWU Local 5: A Brief History of Local 5: Powell\u2019s Books, Inc.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110116051423/http://www.ilwulocal5.com/about/we-are-the-ilwu/we-are-ilwu-local-5/ilwu-local-5-powells-books/history |date=January 16, 2011 }} from the [[International Longshore and Warehouse Union|ILWU]] Local 5 website</ref>  In response to issues identified by the organizing employees, Powell's updated and expanded its employee handbook in April 1992 with changes that addressed processes for problem solving and grievances, the probation and termination procedure, and other employee assistance, among other changes.\n\nIn September 1998, email from Powell's managers announcing reductions in employee\u2019s wage increases prompted the creation of a new organizing committee of 26 employees.  They chose the [[International Longshore and Warehouse Union]] (ILWU) because they could charter their own self-governing [[local union]] which would include about 350 employees serving in a variety of jobs in all stores and in the Internet, corporate, and shipping departments. By March 1999, they filed for a union certification election with the [[National Labor Relations Board]]. A month later, by a vote of 161\u2013155, ILWU Local 5 became official.<ref name=\"ilwu\"/>\n\nIn September 1999, ILWU Local 5 met for the first time with Powell's management, to begin the contract bargaining process.  After some early successes, 2000 saw a slowdown in the discussions, followed by rallies, filings of [[unfair labor practice]]s, an unsuccessful decertification campaign, a one-day shutdown of the shipping department (accompanied by the slashing of a van's tire), and [[Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service (United States)|federal mediation]].  A three-year contract was finally announced in August 2000.<ref name=\"ilwu\"/>\n\nIn February 2011 Powell's announced the layoffs of 31 employees, over 7% of its unionized workforce, in \u201cresponse to the unprecedented, rapidly changing nature of the book industry\". It was the first round of layoffs since the store\u2019s workers formed a union. A union representative said that Powell's had reduced its workforce by about 40 in the prior year through attrition, but felt that layoffs were still necessary because of a decline in sales of new books and a rise in health care costs.<ref name =\"NY Times Arts Beat\">{{cite news| title= Powell\u2019s Books Announces Layoffs | date= February 9, 2011 | url= http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/02/09/powells-books-announces-layoffs/ | first= Julie |last= Bosman | newspaper= [[The New York Times]] Arts Beat blog | accessdate=2011-02-09}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Powell's announced the closing of its five locations and the termination of nearly all employees in mid-March 2020.<ref name=\"latimes2020\">{{cite news |title=Powell\u2019s, Portland\u2019s beloved indie bookstore, will lay off most workers |last1=Pineda |first1=Dorany |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/books/story/2020-03-18/powells-portlands-beloved-indie-bookstore-lays-off-most-workers |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=March 18, 2020 |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The letter released by CEO Emily Powell on March 17, 2020, did not disclose the exact number of employees that were laid off. However, roughly 85% of the 400 members of the company's unionized workforce were terminated.<ref name=\"oregonlive2020\">{{cite news |title=Powell's expands coronavirus layoff, warns it will be 'several months' before normal operations |last1=Rogoway |first1=Mike |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/powells-expands-coronavirus-layoff-warns-it-will-be-several-months-before-normal-operations.html |work=The Oregonian |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> More than 100 former staffers were then rehired to fulfill a large surge of online orders.<ref>http://web.archive.org/web/20200329201856/http://www.powells.com/featured/communitymessage</ref>\n\n=== Politics ===\nPowell's Books was a key opponent of Oregon's [[Oregon Ballot Measure 97 (2016)|Measure 97]], which would have raised corporate taxes to fund schools, healthcare and senior services. Michael Powell contributed $25,000 to the opposition campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://secure.sos.state.or.us/orestar/gotoPublicTransactionDetail.do?tranRsn=2313889|title=Oregon Secretary Of State|website=secure.sos.state.or.us|access-date=2017-01-19}}</ref> Powell's Books was featured in television ads for the No campaign,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Oregon_Business_Tax_Increase,_Measure_97_(2016)|title=Oregon Business Tax Increase, Measure 97 (2016) - Ballotpedia|language=en|access-date=2017-01-19}}</ref> and Emily Powell signed a statement opposing the measure in the voter's pamphlet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sos.oregon.gov/elections/Documents/pamphlet/november-general-2016.aspx|title=Online Voters' Pamphlet {{!}} Oregon Secretary of State|website=sos.oregon.gov|access-date=2017-01-19}}</ref>\n\n== List of locations ==\n[[File:Powell's Books at Cedar Hills Crossing, mall-interior entrance.jpg|thumb|right|Powell's Books at Cedar Hills Crossing]]\nIn addition to its \"City of Books\" location, Powell's Books also has several smaller stores: \n*a {{convert|32500|sqft|adj=on}} general bookstore with the \"largest children's book section of any book store on the West Coast\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.powells.com/locations/powells-books-at-cedar-hills-crossing|title=Powells Books At Cedar Hills Crossing|website=www.powells.com}}</ref> located at [[Cedar Hills Crossing]] in [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]] and opened in November 2006, replacing a 22-year-old location near [[Washington Square (Oregon)|Washington Square]] that was less than half the size;<ref name=\"suburb\">[http://www.powells.com/info/places/beavertoninfo.html Powell's Books at Cedar Hills Crossing] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070227132702/http://www.powells.com/info/places/beavertoninfo.html |date=February 27, 2007 }} from the company's website. Retrieved 2012-07-14.</ref>\n*another in Portland's [[Hawthorne, Portland, Oregon|Hawthorne District]];\n*a store with cooking and gardening materials two spaces east of the Hawthorne store (it was announced in January 2016 that Powell's will be taking over the lease of the space between the general interest store and the home and garden store and combine the two stores into one, with larger children's books and authors' event sections).<ref name=\"expand Hawthorne\">{{cite news|last=Marum|first=Anna|title=Powell's Books to expand Hawthorne location|newspaper=The Oregonian|date=January 6, 2016|orig-year=print-edition date January 8, p. C1|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/window-shop/index.ssf/2016/01/powells_hawthorne_expansion.html|accessdate=2016-02-01}}</ref>\n*one store at the [[Portland International Airport]], offering popular fiction and non-fiction, \"choice\" used books, games, toys, and gifts.<ref>[http://www.powells.com/info/places/airportinfo.html Powell's Books at PDX] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060717040156/http://www.powells.com/info/places/airportinfo.html |date=July 17, 2006 }} from the company's website</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Oregon}}\n* [[Cameron's Books and Magazines]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.powells.com/ Powell's website], including a [https://web.archive.org/web/20140613100109/http://www.powells.com/info/citytour.html tour of the City of Books]\n\n{{coord|45|31|24.04|N|122|40|53.71|W|region:US-OR_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{LA Times Innovator's Award}}\n{{Pearl District, Portland, Oregon}}\n\n[[Category:1971 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1971]]\n[[Category:Antiquarian booksellers]]\n[[Category:Book selling websites]]\n[[Category:Bookstores established in the 20th century]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:E-book suppliers]]\n[[Category:Independent bookstores of the United States]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 1993]]\n[[Category:Online retailers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Pearl District, Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1971]]\n", "name_user": "UpdateNerd", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200elead:combine related pars", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Powell%27s_Books"}
{"title_page": "Conrad Ricamora", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Conrad Ricamora\n| image              = \n| caption            = Ricamora after a performance of Here Lies Love at the Public Theater in 2015\n| image_size         = \n| birth_name         = Conrad Wayne Ricamora<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/cue-a-here-lies-love-star-conrad-ricamora-on-the-immersive-experience-his-r-326486|title=CUE & A: Here Lies Love Star Conrad Ricamora on the Immersive Experience, His Raptor Impression and \"The Golden Girls\"|work=Playbill|accessdate=28 October 2014}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{b-da|February 17, 1979}}\n| birth_place        = [[Santa Maria, California|Santa Maria]], [[California]], U.S.\n| education          = MFA, [[University of Tennessee]]; BA in Psychology, [[Queens University of Charlotte]]\n| occupation         = [[Actor]] & [[Singing|Singer]]\n| years_active       = 2006\u2013present\n| known_for          = ''[[How To Get Away With Murder]]'', ''[[The King And I]]'', ''[[Here Lies Love]]''\n| height             = 6 ft 0 in\n| awards             = \n}}\n\n'''Conrad Wayne Ricamora''' (born February 17, 1979)<ref name=\"cbi\">{{cite web|url=https://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/conrad_wayne_ricamora_born_1979_14193209|work=California Birth Index|publisher=California Office of Health Information and Research|title=Conrad Wayne Ricamora was born on February 17, 1979 in Santa Barbara County, California|accessdate=November 4, 2018}}</ref> is an [[Americans|American]] actor and singer. He is best known for his portrayal of [[List of How to Get Away with Murder characters#Oliver Hampton|Oliver Hampton]] on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] television series ''[[How to Get Away with Murder]]'' (2014\u2013present).\n\n==Biography==\nRicamora was born in Santa Maria, California. He is the son of Ron Ricamora, who was in the [[United States Air Force|US Air Force]], and [[social worker]] Debbie Bolender. His father was born in Manila, Philippines and moved to the US when he was 10. His father is believed to be of [[Filipino people|Filipino]] descent but is adopted,<ref name=\"out\">{{cite web|url=http://www.out.com/entertainment/theater-dance/2014/07/30/here-lies-love-stars-jose-llana-conrad-ricamora-filipino-marcos-musical|title=Jose Llana & Conrad Ricamora, stars of Here Lies Love, on their personal journeys of self-acceptance|work=Out Magazine|accessdate=28 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Inquirer\">{{cite news|last1=Nepales|first1=Ruben V.|title=Fil-Am actor terrific as Ninoy Aquino\u2013Vogue|url=http://entertainment.inquirer.net/93001/fil-am-actor-terrific-as-ninoy-aquino-vogue|accessdate=9 November 2016|work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|date=9 May 2013}}</ref> and his mother is of German and Irish descent.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fierberg|first1=Ruthie|title=Conrad Ricamora Earns the Human Rights Campaign's Visibility Award|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/conrad-ricamora-earns-the-human-rights-campaigns-visibility-award|accessdate=9 November 2016|work=[[Playbill]]|date=1 September 2016}}</ref> Ricamora grew up primarily in Niceville, Florida, and was an avid tennis player.  He is openly gay and was honored with the [[Human Rights Campaign]]'s Visibility Award.<ref>[http://www.towleroad.com/2016/08/conrad-ricamora/ Human Rights Campaign]; \u2014 last visited 25 October 2016.</ref> He is dating a man called Joshua Cockream. \n\n==Career==\nConrad Ricamora performed the role of Ninoy Aquino in the 2013 Off-Broadway musical, ''[[Here Lies Love]]'', which had two runs at [[The Public Theater]]. He won a [[Theatre World Award]] and was nominated for a [[Lucille Lortel Awards|Lucille Lortel Award]] for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Musical.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theatreworldawards.org/past-recipients.html|title=Theatre World Awards - Theatre World Awards|website=www.theatreworldawards.org|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lortel.org/lla_archive/index.cfm?search_by=people&first=Conrad&last=Ricamora&middle= |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-09-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151007165024/http://www.lortel.org/lla_archive/index.cfm?search_by=people&first=Conrad&last=Ricamora&middle= |archive-date=2015-10-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/suzy-evans/on-the-town-summer-friday_b_5698619.html|title=On the Town: Summer Fridays at 'Here Lies Love'|date=22 August 2014|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=28 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, he was cast in the recurring role of Oliver Hampton on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] legal drama series ''[[How to Get Away with Murder]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebacklot.com/how-to-get-away-with-murder-jack-falahee-on-connor-as-a-creature-of-appetites/10/2014/|title=\"How To Get Away With Murder\" Actor Jack Falahee: Connor is a \"Creature Of Appetites\"|work=thebacklot.com|accessdate=28 October 2014}}</ref> He continued to make guest appearances throughout the show's second season and was promoted to a series regular in season three.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2016/03/18/how-to-get-away-with-murder-season-3-conrad-ricamora-series-regular-oliver/|title=HTGAWM Promotes Conrad Ricamora to Series Regular in Season 3|website=TVLine|access-date=2016-03-18}}</ref>\n\nRicamora played Lun Tha in [[Lincoln Center Theater]]'s 2015 Broadway revival of [[Rodgers and Hammerstein]]'s ''[[The King and I]]'', directed by [[Bartlett Sher]].<ref name=\"Brantley2015\">Brantley, Ben. [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/17/theater/review-the-king-and-i-back-on-broadway.html?_r=0 \"Review: ''The King and I'', Back on Broadway\"], ''The New York Times'', April 16, 2015</ref> The 2015 Broadway cast recording of the musical received a [[Grammy Award]] nomination for [[Grammy Award for Best Musical Theater Album|Best Musical Theater Album]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Grammy Nominations 2016 Full List|url = http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/grammy-nominations-2016-full-list-846297|website = The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate = 2015-12-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Ricamora rejoined the cast of [[Here Lies Love]] as Ninoy Aquino at the [[Seattle Repertory Theater]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/theater/review-here-lies-love-is-a-swirling-dynamic-first-ladys-biography-to-a-disco-beat/|title=Review: Seattle Rep\u2019s bold \u2018Here Lies Love\u2019 is an interactive spectacle|date=2017-04-21|website=The Seattle Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Ricamora starred in the premiere of [[David Henry Hwang]]'s ''[[Soft Power (musical)|Soft Power]]'' as Xue Xing at the [[Ahmanson Theatre]] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-ca-cm-soft-power-asian-representation-20180506-story.html|title='Soft Power' has a cast that's almost entirely Asian. Here's why that's a radical idea for American theater|last=Fung|first=Lisa|date=May 3, 2018|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Talladega Nights: The Ballad of Ricky Bobby]]''\n| DMV Officer\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5047336/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_1 ''The Light of The Moon'']\n|Jack\n|\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2014\u2013present\n| ''[[How to Get Away with Murder]]''\n| Oliver Hampton\n| 75 episodes {{small|(recurring role, seasons 1-2; series regular, season 3-)}}\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Mental''\n| Dr. Torres\n| Episode: ''Dr. Bleiffer is on Maternity Leave''\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Theatre ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|2018\n|''Soft Power''\n|Xue Xing\n|\n|-\n| 2013\u20132017\n| ''[[Here Lies Love]]''\n| Ninoy Aquino\n| [[Theatre World Award]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[Lucille Lortel Awards|Lucille Lortel Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Musical]]\n|-\n| 2015\u20132016\n| ''[[The King and I]]''\n| Lun Tha\n| [[Grammy Award|The Grammy Award]]\n\nNominated\u2014[[Best Musical Theater Album]], Principal Soloist\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|1505056}}\n* [http://www.ibdb.com/Person/View/494762 Conrad Ricamora] at the [[Internet Broadway Database]]\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ricamora, Conrad}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Theatre World Award winners]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Gay actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Filipino descent]]\n[[Category:American male actors of Filipino descent]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:LGBT American people of Asian descent]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from California]]\n[[Category:Queens University of Charlotte alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Tennessee alumni]]\n[[Category:Male actors of German descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Conrad Ricamora\n| image              = \n| caption            = Ricamora after a performance of Here Lies Love at the Public Theater in 2015\n| image_size         = \n| birth_name         = Conrad Wayne Ricamora<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/cue-a-here-lies-love-star-conrad-ricamora-on-the-immersive-experience-his-r-326486|title=CUE & A: Here Lies Love Star Conrad Ricamora on the Immersive Experience, His Raptor Impression and \"The Golden Girls\"|work=Playbill|accessdate=28 October 2014}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{b-da|February 17, 1979}}\n| birth_place        = [[Santa Maria, California|Santa Maria]], [[California]], U.S.\n| education          = MFA, [[University of Tennessee]]; BA in Psychology, [[Queens Univers